{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531974"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:21:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:21:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14643"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14643"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.3,0.01,0.07,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7336"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93214"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7336"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14643"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76535"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1708"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3934"},{"type":"tags","id":"3939"},{"type":"tags","id":"3960"},{"type":"tags","id":"4625"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17903"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29733"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93214"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man is admitted to the rehabilitation ward three days after a left middle cerebral artery territory infarct. He has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and hypercholesterolaemia. His regular medications are metformin, perindopril, aspirin, and atorvastatin. He previously worked as an accountant and lives with his wife.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears stable with vital signs within normal limits. He is alert but has difficulty maintaining attention during conversations and requires frequent redirection. His speech is non-fluent with preserved comprehension but marked difficulty with expression and word-finding (Broca\u0027s aphasia). He has right-sided hemiparesis affecting his arm more than leg (power 2/5 in right arm, 3/5 in right leg). He requires moderate assistance for transfers and is not yet mobile. Sensation is intact. His swallow has been assessed as safe for regular diet and thin fluids.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first priority for rehabilitation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Early mobilisation and gait training","Speech and language therapy","Upper limb splinting","Intensive physiotherapy for upper limb strengthening","Cognitive rehabilitation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical deficits following a left middle cerebral artery stroke, including Broca\u0027s aphasia, attention deficits, and right hemiparesis. While all aspects of rehabilitation are important, evidence supports prioritising certain interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEarly mobilisation and gait training\u003C/strong\u003E should be the first priority in stroke rehabilitation, provided the patient is medically stable. Research shows that early mobilisation within 24-48 hours of stroke improves functional outcomes and reduces complications such as deep vein thrombosis, chest infections, and pressure injuries. The ability to mobilise independently also facilitates participation in other rehabilitation activities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntensive physiotherapy for upper limb strengthening\u003C/strong\u003E, while important, is typically not the first priority as lower limb function and mobility are more crucial for basic activities of daily living and independence. Upper limb rehabilitation can be initiated concurrently with mobility training but should not delay mobilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECognitive rehabilitation\u003C/strong\u003E would address the patient\u0027s attention deficits, but is less urgent than establishing basic mobility. Cognitive training can be incorporated into the rehabilitation program once basic mobility is established, and attention can be addressed within the context of other therapeutic activities. There is some evidence of its efficacy and it has a weak recommendation as per the Australian and New Zealand Living Clinical Guidelines for Stroke Management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpper limb splinting\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered for prevention of contractures but is not recommended as part of routine practice, given lack of evidence in improving function, pain or range of movement post stroke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpeech and language therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is certainly important for this patient with Broca\u0027s aphasia, but should not delay physical mobilisation. Speech therapy can be conducted concurrently with mobility training as part of a comprehensive rehabilitation program.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in stroke rehabilitation is to adopt a multidisciplinary approach that addresses all impairments while prioritising interventions that will facilitate independence and prevent complications. Early mobilisation forms the foundation for successful rehabilitation and enables participation in other therapeutic activities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Early mobilisation within 24-48 hours improves functional outcomes in stroke rehabilitation, provided the patient is medically stable.","Speech and language therapy should be initiated early for patients with post-stroke aphasia to maximise recovery potential.","A multidisciplinary approach involving physiotherapy, occupational therapy, and speech therapy is essential for optimal stroke rehabilitation outcomes."],"references":["Stroke Foundation. Clinical Guidelines for Stroke Management. Available at https://informme.org.au/en/Guidelines/Clinical-Guidelines-for-Stroke-Management. Chapter 5 Rehabilitation. Accessed [26/10/2024 ]. Available online at ; https://informme.org.au/guidelines/living-clinical-guidelines-for-stroke-management"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76535"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14643"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76535"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-20T21:37:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-20T21:38:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7336"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93214"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null